# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: windows-forms
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] In computer programming, a **callback** is a programming pattern in which a function reference is passed from one context (consumer) to another (provider) such that the provider can call the function.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] If the function accesses state or functionality of the consumer, then the call is *back* to the consumer – backwards compared to the normal flow of control in which a consumer calls a provider.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] A function that accepts a callback parameter may be designed to call back before returning to its caller.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] But, more typically, a callback reference is stored by the provider so that it can call the function later (as *deferred*).
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] If the provider invokes the callback on the same thread as the consumer, then the call is *blocking*, a.k.a.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] If instead, the provider invokes the callback on a different thread, then the call is *non-blocking*, a.k.a.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] A callback can be likened to leaving instructions with a tailor for what to do when a suit is ready, such as calling a specific phone number or delivering it to a given address.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] These instructions represent a callback: a function provided in advance to be executed later, often by a different part of the system and not necessarily by the one that received it.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] The difference between a general function reference and a callback can be subtle, and some use the terms interchangeably but distinction generally depends on programming intent.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] If the intent is like the telephone callback – that the original called party communicates back to the original caller – then it's a callback.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] A blocking callback runs in the execution context of the function that passes the callback.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] A deferred callback can run in a different context such as during interrupt or from a thread.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] As such, a deferred callback can be used for synchronization and delegating work to another thread.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] A callback can be used for event handling.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] Often, consuming code registers a callback for a particular type of event.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] When that event occurs, the callback is called.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] Callbacks are often used to program the graphical user interface (GUI) of a program that runs in a windowing system.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] The application supplies a reference to a custom callback function for the windowing system to call.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] The windowing system calls this function to notify the application of events like mouse clicks and key presses.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] A callback can be used to implement asynchronous processing.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] A caller requests an action and provides a callback to be called when the action completes which might be long after the request is made.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] A callback can be used to implement polymorphism.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] In the following pseudocode, `say_hi` can take either `write_status` or `write_error`.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] The callback technology is implemented differently by programming language.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] In assembly, C, C++, Pascal, Modula-2 and other languages, a callback function is stored internally as a function pointer.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] Using the same storage allows different languages to directly share callbacks without a design-time or runtime interoperability layer.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] For example, the Windows API is accessible via multiple languages, compilers and assemblers.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] C++ also allows objects to provide an implementation of the function call operation.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] The Standard Template Library accepts these objects (called *functors*) as parameters.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] Many dynamic languages, such as JavaScript, Lua, Python, Perl and PHP, allow a function object to be passed.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] CLI languages such as C# and Visual Basic (.NET) (VB.NET) provide a type-safe encapsulating function reference known as delegate.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] Events and event handlers, as used in .NET languages, provide for callbacks.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] Functional programming languages generally support first-class functions, which can be passed as callbacks to other functions, stored as data or returned from functions.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] Many languages, including Perl, Python, Ruby, Smalltalk, C++ (11+), C# and VB.NET (new versions) and most functional languages, support lambda expressions, unnamed functions with inline syntax, that generally act as callbacks.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] In some languages, including Scheme, ML, JavaScript, Perl, Python, Smalltalk, PHP (since 5.3.0), C++ (11+), Java (since 8), and many others, a lambda can be a closure, i.e., can access variables locally defined in the context in which the lambda is defined.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] In an object-oriented programming language such as Java versions before function-valued arguments, the behavior of a callback can be achieved by passing an object that implements an interface.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] The methods of this object are callbacks.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] In PL/I and ALGOL 60, a callback procedure may need to be able to access local variables in containing blocks, so it is called through an *entry variable* containing both the entry point and context information.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] Callbacks have a wide variety of uses, for example in error signaling: a Unix program might not want to terminate immediately when it receives SIGTERM, so to make sure that its termination is handled properly, it would register the cleanup function as a callback.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] Another common use for callbacks in C is with C standard library functions used for sorting (`qsort()`) and searching (`lsearch()`, `bsearch()`) where a comparator function is passed as an argument to the routine to determine the collation order.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] Callbacks may also be used to control whether a function acts or not: Xlib allows custom predicates to be specified to determine whether a program wishes to handle an event.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] In the following C code, function `printNumber()` uses parameter `getNumber` as a blocking callback.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] `printNumber()` is called with `getAnswerToMostImportantQuestion()` which acts as a callback function.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] In C++, functors can be used in addition to function pointer.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] A functor is an object with `operator()` defined.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] For example, the objects in `std::views` are functors.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] In the following C# code, method `Helper.PerformAction` uses parameter `callback` as a blocking callback.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] `Helper.PerformAction` is called with `Log` which acts as a callback function.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] When run, the following is written to the console: "Callback was: Hello world".
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] In the following JavaScript code, function `calculate` uses parameter `operate` as a blocking callback.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] `calculate` is called with `multiply` and then with `sum` which act as callback functions.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] The collection method `.each()` of the jQuery library uses the function passed to it as a blocking callback.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] It calls the callback for each item of the collection.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] Deferred callbacks are commonly used for handling events from the user, the client and timers.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] Examples can be found in `addEventListener`, Ajax and `XMLHttpRequest`.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] In addition to using callbacks in JavaScript source code, C functions that take a function are supported via js-ctypes.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] In the following Julia code, function `calculate` accepts a parameter `operate` that is used as a blocking callback.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] `calculate` is called with `square` which acts as a callback function.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] In the following Kotlin code, function `askAndAnswer` uses parameter `getAnswer` as a blocking callback.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] `askAndAnswer` is called with `getAnswerToMostImportantQuestion` which acts as a callback function.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] Running this will tell the user that the answer to their question is "42".
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] In this Lua code, function `calculate` accepts the `operation` parameter which is used as a blocking callback.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] `calculate` is called with both `add` and `multiply`, and then uses an anonymous function to divide.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] In the following Python code, function `calculate` accepts a parameter `operate` that is used as a blocking callback.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] The following Rebol and Red code demonstrates callback use.
[src:windows-forms/callback-computer-programming] Rust have the `Fn`, `FnMut` and `FnOnce` traits.
[src:windows-forms/common-language-runtime] The **Common Language Runtime** (**CLR**), the virtual machine component of Microsoft .NET Framework, manages the execution of .NET programs.
[src:windows-forms/common-language-runtime] Just-in-time compilation converts the managed code (compiled intermediate language code) into machine instructions which are then executed on the CPU of the computer.
[src:windows-forms/common-language-runtime] The CLR provides additional services including memory management, type safety, exception handling, garbage collection, security and thread management.
[src:windows-forms/common-language-runtime] All programs written for the .NET Framework, regardless of programming language, are executed in the CLR.
[src:windows-forms/common-language-runtime] All versions of the .NET Framework include CLR.
[src:windows-forms/common-language-runtime] CLR implements the Virtual Execution System (VES) as defined in the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) standard, initially developed by Microsoft itself.
[src:windows-forms/common-language-runtime] A public standard defines the Common Language Infrastructure specification.
[src:windows-forms/common-language-runtime] During the transition from legacy .NET technologies like the .NET Framework and its proprietary runtime to the community-developed .NET Core, the CLR was dubbed **CoreCLR**.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] In computer programming, **event-driven programming** is a programming paradigm in which the flow of the program is determined by external events.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] User interface (UI) events from keyboards and mice, touchpads and touchscreens, and external sensor inputs are common cases.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] Events may also be programmatically generated, such as from messages from other programs, notifications from other threads, or other network events.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programming is the dominant paradigm used in graphical user interface (GUI) applications and network servers.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] In an event-driven application, there is generally an event loop that listens for events and then triggers a callback function when one of those events is detected.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programs can be written in any programming language, although the task is easier in languages that provide high-level abstractions.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] Although they do not exactly fit the event-driven model, interrupt handling and exception handling have many similarities.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] It is important to differentiate between event-driven and message-driven (aka queue-driven) paradigms: event-driven services (e.g.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] AWS SNS) are decoupled from their consumers, whereas message/queue-driven services (e.g.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] AWS SQS) are coupled with their consumers.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] Because the event loop that retrieves and dispatches events is common amongst applications, many programming frameworks provide an implementation of an event loop, and the application developer only needs to write the event handlers.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] The actual logic is contained in event handler routines.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] These routines handle the events to which the main program will respond.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] For example, a single mouse-click on a "Save" command button in a GUI program might trigger a routine to save data to a database.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] An "Exit" button might trigger a routine to exit the program.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] The event loop receives events from all such command buttons and other GUI elements, dispatching the appropriate event handler routine for each button.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] Event handler routines need to be bound to specific events, so the event loop can dispatch the correct routine in response to the event.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] Many IDEs simplify this process by providing the programmer with an event handling template for each specific event (such as a button click), allowing the programmer to focus on writing the event-handling code.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] In a sequential program, keeping track of execution order and history is normally trivial.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] But in an event-driven program, event handlers execute non-sequentially in response to external events.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] Special attention and planning is required to correctly structure the event handlers to work when called in any order.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] Most existing GUI architectures use event-driven programming.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] The Java AWT framework processes all UI changes on a single thread, called the Event dispatching thread.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] Similarly, all UI updates in the Java framework JavaFX occur on the JavaFX Application Thread.
[src:windows-forms/event-driven-programming] Most network servers and frameworks such as Node.js are also event-driven.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] The **message loop** is an obligatory section of code in every program that uses a graphical user interface under Microsoft Windows.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] Windows programs that have a GUI are event-driven.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] Windows maintains an individual message queue for each thread that has created a window.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] Usually only the first thread creates windows.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] Windows places messages into that queue whenever mouse activity occurs on that thread's window, whenever keyboard activity occurs while that window has focus, and at other times.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] A process can also add messages to its own queue.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] To accept user input, and for other reasons, each thread with a window must continuously retrieve messages from its queue, and act on them.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] A programmer makes the process do that by writing a loop that calls GetMessage (which blocks for a message and retrieves it), and then calls DispatchMessage (which dispatches the message), and repeats indefinitely.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] There usually is a message loop in the main program, which runs on the main thread, and additional message loop in each created modal dialog.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] Messages for *every* window of the process pass through its message queue, and are handled by its message loop.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] A message loop is one kind of event loop.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] It is conventional for the event loop to call `TranslateMessage` on each message which can translate virtual keystrokes into strings.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] Calling `TranslateMessage` is not technically required, but problems can result if it is not called.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] The message loop must call `DispatchMessage`.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] The message loop does not directly act on the messages that it handles.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] It dispatches them by calling `DispatchMessage`, which transfers the message to the "window procedure" for the window that the message was addressed to.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] Code can also send messages directly to a window procedure.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] A strict message loop is not the only option.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] Code elsewhere in the program can also accept and dispatch messages.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] `PeekMessage` is a non-blocking call that returns immediately, with a message if any are waiting, or no message if none is waiting.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] `WaitMessage` allows a thread to sleep until a message is in the queue.
[src:windows-forms/message-loop-in-microsoft-windows] However, each framework implements a message loop somewhere, and the message loop can usually be accessed or replaced when more direct control is required.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The **Windows API**, informally **WinAPI**, is the foundational application programming interface (API) that allows a computer program to access the features of the Microsoft Windows operating system in which the program is running.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Programs typically access this API using system libraries, which are shared libraries.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Each major version of the Windows API has a distinct name that identifies a compatibility aspect of that version.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] For example, Win32 is the major version of Windows API that runs on 32-bit systems.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The name, Windows API, collectively refers to all versions of this capability of Windows.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Microsoft provides developer support via a software development kit, Microsoft Windows SDK, which includes documentation and tools for building software based on the Windows API.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] This section lists notable services provided by the Windows API.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Base services include features such as the file system, devices, processes, threads, and error handling.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] These functions reside in kernel.exe, krnl286.exe or krnl386.exe files on 16-bit Windows, and kernel32.dll and KernelBase.dll on 32 and 64 bit Windows.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] These files reside in the folder \Windows\System32 on all versions of Windows.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Advanced services include features beyond the kernel like the Windows registry, shutdown/restart the system (or abort), start/stop/create a Windows service, manage user accounts.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] These functions reside in advapi32.dll and advapires32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The Graphics Device Interface (GDI) component provides features to output graphics content to monitors, printers, and other output devices.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] It resides in gdi.exe on 16-bit Windows, and gdi32.dll on 32-bit Windows in user-mode.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Kernel-mode GDI support is provided by `win32k.sys` which communicates directly with the graphics driver.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The User Interface component provides features to create and manage screen windows and most basic controls, such as buttons and scrollbars, receive mouse and keyboard input, and other functions associated with the graphical user interface (GUI) part of Windows.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] This functional unit resides in user.exe on 16-bit Windows, and user32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Since Windows XP versions, the basic controls reside in comctl32.dll, together with the common controls (Common Control Library).
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The Common Dialog Box Library provides standard dialog boxes to open and save files, choose color and font, etc.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The library resides in a file called commdlg.dll on 16-bit Windows, and comdlg32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] It is grouped under the *User Interface* category of the API.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The Common Control Library provides access to advanced user interface controls, including things like status bars, progress bars, toolbars and tabs.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The library resides in a DLL file called commctrl.dll on 16-bit Windows, and comctl32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The Windows Shell component provides access to the operating system shell.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The component resides in shell.dll on 16-bit Windows, and shell32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The Shell Lightweight Utility Functions are in shlwapi.dll.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Network Services provide access to the various networking abilities of the operating system.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Its subcomponents include NetBIOS, Winsock, NetDDE, remote procedure call (RPC) and many more.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] This component resides in netapi32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The Internet Explorer (IE) web browser exposes APIs and as such could be considered part of the Windows API.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] IE has been included with the operating system since Windows 95 OSR2 and has provided web-related services to applications since Windows 98.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The Windows API is a C language-based API.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Functions and data structures are consumable via C syntax by including windows.h, but the API can be consumed via any programming language that can inter-operate with the API data structures and calling conventions for function calls and callbacks.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Of note, the implementation of API functions has been developed in several languages other than C.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Despite the fact that C is not an object-oriented programming (OOP) language, the Windows API is somewhat object-oriented due to its use of handles.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Various other technologies from Microsoft and others make this object-oriented aspect more apparent by using an OOP language such as C++ — see Microsoft Foundation Class Library (MFC), Visual Component Library (VCL), GDI+.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Of note, Windows 8 provides the Windows API and the WinRT API, which is implemented in C++ and is object-oriented by design.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Windows.pas is a Delphi unit that exposes the features of Windows API – the Pascal equivalent of windows.h.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Many Microsoft technologies use the Windows API—as most software running on Windows does.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] As middle-ware between Windows API and an application, the following technologies provide some access to Windows API.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Some technologies are described as wrapping Windows API, but this is debatable since they don't provide or expose all of the capabilities of Windows API.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Although almost all Windows programs use the Windows API, on the Windows NT line of operating systems, programs that start early in the Windows startup process use the Native API instead.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The Windows API has always exposed a large part of the underlying structure of the Windows systems to programmers.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] This had the advantage of giving them much flexibility and power over their applications, but also creates great responsibility in how applications handle various low-level, sometimes tedious, operations that are associated with a graphical user interface.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] For example, a beginning C programmer will often write the simple "hello world" as their first assignment.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The working part of the program is only a single printf line within the main subroutine.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Charles Petzold, who wrote several books about programming for the Windows API, said: "The original hello world program in the Windows 1.0 SDK was a bit of a scandal.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] HELLO.C was about 150 lines long, and the HELLO.RC resource script had another 20 or so more lines.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] (...) Veteran programmers often curled up in horror or laughter when encountering the Windows hello-world program." Petzold explains that while it was the first Windows sample programs developers were introduced to, it was quite "fancy" and more complex than needed.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Tired of people ridiculing the length of the sample, he eventually reduced it to a simple MessageBox call.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Over the years, various changes and additions were made to Windows systems, and the Windows API changed and grew to reflect this.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The Windows API for Windows 1.0 supported fewer than 450 function calls, whereas modern versions of the Windows API support thousands.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] However, in general, the interface remained fairly consistent, and an old Windows 1.0 application will still look familiar to a programmer who is used to the modern Windows API.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Microsoft has made an effort to maintain backward compatibility.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] To achieve this, when developing new versions of Windows, Microsoft sometimes implemented workarounds to allow compatibility with third-party software that used the prior version in an undocumented or even inadvisable way.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Raymond Chen, a Microsoft developer who works on the Windows API, has said: "I could probably write for months solely about bad things apps do and what we had to do to get them to work again (often in spite of themselves).
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Which is why I get particularly furious when people accuse Microsoft of maliciously breaking applications during OS upgrades.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] One of the largest changes to the Windows API was the transition from Win16 (shipped in Windows 3.1 and older) to Win32 (Windows NT and Windows 95 and up).
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] While Win32 was originally introduced with Windows NT 3.1 and Win32s allowed use of a Win32 subset before Windows 95, it was not until Windows 95 that widespread porting of applications to Win32 began.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] To ease the transition, in Windows 95, for developers outside and inside Microsoft, a complex scheme of API thunks was used that could allow 32-bit code to call into 16-bit code (for most of Win16 APIs) and vice versa.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] *Flat thunks* allowed 32-bit code to call into 16-bit libraries, and the scheme was used extensively inside Windows 95's libraries to avoid porting the whole OS to Win32 in one batch.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] In Windows NT, the OS was pure 32-bit, except parts for compatibility with 16-bit applications, and only generic thunks were available to thunk from Win16 to Win32, as for Windows 95.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The Platform SDK shipped with a compiler that could produce the code needed for these thunks.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Versions of 64-bit Windows are also able to run 32-bit applications via WoW64.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The SysWOW64 folder located in the Windows folder on the OS drive contains several tools to support 32-bit applications.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Each version of Microsoft Windows contains a version of Windows API, and almost every new version of Microsoft Windows has introduced additions and changes to the Windows API.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The name, Windows API, refers to essentially the same capability in each version of Windows, but there is another name for this capability that is based on major architectural aspects of the Windows version that contains it.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] When there was only one version, it was simply called Windows API.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Then, when the first major update was made, Microsoft gave it the name Win32 and gave the first version the name Win16.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The term Windows API refers to both versions and all subsequently developed major versions.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The Wine project provides a Win32 API compatibility layer for Unix-like platforms, between Linux kernel API and programs written for the Windows API.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] ReactOS goes a step further and aims to implement the full Windows operating system, working closely with the Wine project to promote code re-use and compatibility.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] DosWin32 and HX DOS Extender are other projects which emulate the Windows API to allow executing simple Windows programs from a DOS command line.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Odin is a project to emulate Win32 on OS/2, superseding the original Win-OS/2 emulation which was based on Microsoft code.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Other minor implementations include the MEWEL and Zinc libraries which were intended to implement a subset of the Win16 API on DOS (see List of platform-independent GUI libraries).
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Windows Interface Source Environment (WISE) was a licensing program from Microsoft which allowed developers to recompile and run Windows-based applications on Unix and Macintosh platforms.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] WISE SDKs were based on an emulator of the Windows API that could run on those platforms.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] To develop software that uses the Windows API, a compiler must be able to use the Microsoft-specific DLLs listed above (COM-objects are outside Win32 and assume a certain vtable layout).
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The compiler must either handle the header files that expose the interior API function names, or supply such files.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] For the language C++, Zortech (later Symantec, then Digital Mars), Watcom and Borland have all produced well-known commercial compilers that have been used often with Win16, Win32s, and Win32.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Some of them supplied *memory extenders*, allowing Win32 programs to run on Win16 with Microsoft's redistributable Win32s DLL.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The Zortech compiler was probably one of the first stable and usable C++ compilers for Windows programming, before Microsoft had a C++ compiler.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] For certain classes of applications, the compiler system should also be able to handle interface description language (IDL) files.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Collectively, these prerequisites (compilers, tools, libraries, and headers) are known as the *Microsoft Platform SDK*.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] As of 2016, the MinGW and Cygwin projects also provide such an environment based on the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), using a stand-alone header file set, to make linking against the Win32-specific DLLs simple.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] LCC-Win32 is a C compiler maintained by Jacob Navia, freeware for non-commercial use.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Pelles C is a freeware C compiler maintained by Pelle Orinius.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Free Pascal is a free software Object Pascal compiler that supports the Windows API.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The MASM32 package is a mature project providing support for the Windows API under Microsoft Macro Assembler (MASM) by using custom made or converted headers and libraries from the Platform SDK.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Flat assembler FASM allows building Windows programs without using an external linker, even when running on Linux.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Windows specific compiler support is also needed for Structured Exception Handling (SEH).
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] This system serves two purposes: it provides a substrate on which language-specific exception handling can be implemented, and it is how the kernel notifies applications of exceptional conditions such as dereferencing an invalid pointer or stack overflow.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] The Microsoft/Borland C++ compilers had the ability to use this system as soon as it was introduced in Windows 95 and NT, however the actual implementation was undocumented and had to be reverse engineered for the Wine project and free compilers.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] SEH is based on pushing exception handler frames onto the stack, then adding them to a linked list stored in thread-local storage (the first field of the thread environment block).
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] When an exception is thrown, the kernel and base libraries unwind the stack running handlers and filters as they are encountered.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Eventually, every exception unhandled by the application will be dealt with by the default backstop handler, which pops up the Windows common crash dialog.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Microsoft has plans to update the Windows API for modern C++ usage with their `win32metadata` project.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Currently, there is C++/WinRT and "Windows Implementation Library" (WIL) for doing this in modern C++.
[src:windows-forms/windows-api] Microsoft has also created bindings for other languages, including C# and Rust for calling the Win32 API.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] At the Microsoft Connect event on December 4, 2018, Microsoft announced releasing Windows Forms as an open source project on GitHub.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] With this release, Windows Forms has become available for projects targeting the .NET Core framework.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] However, the framework is still available only on the Windows platform, and Mono's incomplete implementation of Windows Forms remains the only cross-platform implementation.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] A *Windows Forms application* is an event-driven application supported by Microsoft's .NET Framework.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] Unlike a batch program, it spends most of its time simply waiting for the user to do something, such as fill in a text box or click a button.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] The code for the application can be written in a .NET programming language such as C# or Visual Basic.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] Windows Forms provides access to native Windows User Interface Common Controls by wrapping the existent Windows API in managed code.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] With the help of Windows Forms, the .NET Framework provides a more comprehensive abstraction above the Win32 API than Visual Basic or MFC did.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] Windows Forms is similar to Microsoft Foundation Class (MFC) library in developing client applications.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] It provides a wrapper consisting of a set of C++ classes for development of Windows applications.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] However, it does not provide a default application framework like the MFC.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] Every control in a Windows Forms application is a concrete instance of a class.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] All visual elements in the Windows Forms class library derive from the Control class.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] This provides the minimal functionality of a user interface element such as location, size, color, font, text, as well as common events like click and drag/drop.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] The Control class also has docking support to let a control rearrange its position under its parent.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] The Microsoft Active Accessibility support in the Control class also helps impaired users to use Windows Forms better.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] In Visual Studio, forms are created using drag-and-drop techniques.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] A tool is used to place controls (e.g., text boxes, buttons, etc.) on the form (window).
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] Controls have attributes and event handlers associated with them.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] Default values are provided when the control is created, but may be changed by the programmer.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] Many attribute values can be modified during run time based on user actions or changes in the environment, providing a dynamic application.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] For example, code can be inserted into the form resize event handler to reposition a control so that it remains centered on the form, expands to fill up the form, etc.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] By inserting code into the event handler for a keypress in a text box, the program can automatically translate the case of the text being entered, or even prevent certain characters from being inserted.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] Besides providing access to native Windows controls like button, textbox, checkbox and listview, Windows Forms added its own controls for ActiveX hosting, layout arrangement, validation and rich data binding.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] Just like Abstract Window Toolkit (AWT), the equivalent Java API, Windows Forms was an early and easy way to provide graphical user interface components to the .NET Framework.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] Windows Forms is built on the existing Windows API and some controls merely wrap underlying Windows components.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] Some of the methods allow direct access to Win32 callbacks, which are not available in non-Windows platforms.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] In .NET Framework 2.0, Windows Forms gained richer layout controls, Office 2003 style toolstrip controls, multithreading component, richer design-time and data binding support as well as ClickOnce for web-based deployment.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] With the release of .NET Framework 3.0, Microsoft released a second, parallel API for rendering GUIs: Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF) based on DirectX, together with a GUI declarative language called XAML.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] During a question-and-answer session at the Build 2014 Conference, Microsoft explained that Windows Forms was under maintenance mode, with no new features being added, but bugs found would still be fixed.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] Most recently, improved high-DPI support for various Windows Forms controls was introduced in updates to .NET Framework version 4.5.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] For future development, Microsoft has succeeded Windows Forms with a XAML-based GUI entry using frameworks such as WPF and UWP.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] However, drag and drop placement of GUI components in a manner similar to Windows Forms is still provided in XAML by replacing the root XAML element of the Page/Window with a "Canvas" UI-Control.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] When making this change, the user can build a window in a similar fashion as in Windows Forms by directly dragging and dropping components using the Visual Studio GUI.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] While XAML provides drag and drop placement backwards compatibility through the Canvas Control, XAML Controls are only similar to Windows Forms Controls and are not one-to-one backwards compatible.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] They perform similar functions and have a similar appearance, but the properties and methods are different enough to require remapping from one API to another.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] Mono is a project led by Xamarin (formerly by Ximian, then Novell) to create an Ecma standard compliant .NET Framework compatible set of tools.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] In 2011, Mono's support for System.Windows.Forms as of .NET 2.0 was announced as complete; System.Windows.Forms 2.0 works natively on Mac OS X.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] However, System.Windows.Forms has not been actively developed on Mono.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] Full compatibility with .NET was not possible, because Microsoft's System.Windows Forms is mainly a wrapper around the Windows API, and some of the methods allow direct access to Win32 callbacks, which are not available in platforms other than Windows.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] Mono's WinForms implementation is based on Mono's libgdiplus, which implements GDI+ on top of Gtk and Pango.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] A more significant problem is that, since version 5.2, Mono has been upgraded so that its default is to assume a 64 bit platform.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] However, System.Windows.Forms on Mono for the Macintosh OS X platform has been built using a 32 bit subsystem, Carbon.
[src:windows-forms/windows-forms] As of this date, a 64-bit version of System.Windows.Forms for use on Mac OS X remains unavailable and only .NET applications built for the 32 bit platform can be expected to execute.
